What is the difference between Classic Pipeline and YAML Pipeline?

This is a very common Azure DevOps interview question.

Classic Pipeline	YAML Pipeline
Created using Azure DevOps UI	Created using YAML code
Configuration stored in Azure DevOps	Configuration stored in Git repository
Drag-and-drop tasks	Pipeline as Code
Harder to track changes	Easy to track changes using Git
Less reusable	More reusable and version controlled
Good for beginners	Preferred in modern DevOps projects
Interview Answer

Classic Pipeline is created and managed through the Azure DevOps graphical user interface using drag-and-drop tasks. YAML Pipeline is defined using code in a .yml file and stored in a Git repository. 
YAML pipelines support version control, reusability, and automation, which makes them the preferred approach in modern DevOps environments.

Project-Based Answer

In my project, we used both Classic and YAML pipelines. Classic pipelines were used in some legacy applications, while YAML pipelines were used for new implementations because they are easier to maintain, version control, and reuse across environments.

Example YAML Pipeline
trigger:
- main

pool:
  vmImage: ubuntu-latest

steps:
- script: echo "Build Started"
